Here is a simple implementation of a chat server in Java using sockets. This program creates a ServerSocket and waits for clients to connect. When a client connects, it starts a new thread to handle the communication with that client.

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.net.*;
import java.util.*;

public class ChatServer {
    private static final int PORT = 9090;
    private static HashSet<String> names = new HashSet<>();
    private static HashSet<PrintWriter> writers = new HashSet<>();

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        System.out.println("The chat server is running.");
        try (ServerSocket listener = new ServerSocket(PORT)) {
            while (true) {
                new Handler(listener.accept()).start();
            }
        }
    }

    private static class Handler extends Thread {
        private String name;
        private Socket socket;
        private BufferedReader in;
        private PrintWriter out;

        public Handler(Socket socket) {
            this.socket = socket;
        }

        public void run() {
            try {
                in = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(socket.getInputStream()));
                out = new PrintWriter(socket.getOutputStream(), true);

                while (true) {
                    out.println("SUBMITNAME");
                    name = in.readLine();
                    if (name == null) {
                        return;
                    }
                    synchronized (names) {
                        if (!names.contains(name)) {
                            names.add(name);
                            break;
                        }
                    }
                }

                out.println("NAMEACCEPTED " + name);
                for (PrintWriter writer : writers) {
                    writer.println("MESSAGE " + name + " has joined");
                }
                writers.add(out);

                while (true) {
                    String input = in.readLine();
                    if (input == null || input.toLowerCase().equals("/quit")) {
                        return;
                    }
                    for (PrintWriter writer : writers) {
                        writer.println("MESSAGE " + name + ": " + input);
                    }
                }
            } catch (IOException e) {
                System.out.println(e);
            } finally {
                if (out != null) {
                    writers.remove(out);
                }
                if (name != null) {
                    System.out.println(name + " is leaving");
                    names.remove(name);
                    for (PrintWriter writer : writers) {
                        writer.println("MESSAGE " + name + " has left");
                    }
                }
                try {socket.close();} catch (IOException e) {}
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This server communicates with its clients by sending strings back and forth. The protocol it uses is very simple:

- When a client first connects, the server requests a unique username by sending the string `SUBMITNAME`.
- Once a unique username is received, the server acknowledges acceptance by sending the string `NAMEACCEPTED`, followed by the accepted username.
- After a client's username has been accepted, any message it sends will be broadcast to all connected clients prefixed with `MESSAGE`.

A client can disconnect from the server simply by closing its connection. Any messages sent after the client's username has been accepted will be broadcast to all connected clients.

