Here's a simple Golang program that accepts user input for a URL, downloads the corresponding webpage's HTML source code, and saves it into a local file with proper error handling:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"io/ioutil"
	"net/http"
	"os"
	"strings"
)

func main() {
	fmt.Print("Enter the URL: ")
	var url string
	fmt.Scanln(&url)

	if !strings.HasPrefix(url, "http://") && !strings.HasPrefix(url, "https://") {
		url = "http://" + url
	}

	resp, err := http.Get(url)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println("Error fetching the URL:", err)
		return
	}
	defer resp.Body.Close()

	if resp.StatusCode != 200 {
		fmt.Printf("Error: non-200 status code received (%d)\n", resp.StatusCode)
		return
	}

	body, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println("Error reading response body:", err)
		return
	}

	filename := "output.html"
	err = ioutil.WriteFile(filename, body, 0644)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println("Error writing to file:", err)
		return
	}

	fmt.Printf("HTML source code saved to %s\n", filename)
}
```

To run this program, save it as `main.go` and then execute the following command in your terminal:

```sh
go run main.go
```

The program will prompt you to enter a URL. After entering the URL, press Enter, and the program will download the HTML source code of the specified webpage and save it to a file named `output.html`. If there are any errors during the process, they will be displayed on the console.

To create a Node.js Express application that serves as a RESTful API for managing a collection of books, follow these steps:

1. Install the required packages

First, make sure you have Node.js installed on your system. Then, create a new directory for your project and navigate to it in your terminal.

Run the following command to initialize a new Node.js project:

```
npm init -y
```

Next, install the necessary packages by running:

```
npm install express body-parser
```

2. Create an `app.js` file

Create a new file named `app.js` in your project directory. This will be the main entry point for your application.

3. Set up the Express server

Open the `app.js` file and add the following code to set up the Express server:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');

const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json());

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server is running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

4. Define the book data structure and initial data

Add the following code to `app.js` to define the book data structure and some initial data:

```javascript
let books = [
  { id: 1, title: 'Book 1', author: 'Author 1' },
  { id: 2, title: 'Book 2', author: 'Author 2' },
  { id: 3, title: 'Book 3', author: 'Author 3' },
];

let nextId = 4;
```

5. Implement the CRUD endpoints

Now, implement the endpoints for creating, reading, updating, and deleting books, as well as searching for books by title or author. Add the following code to `app.js`:

```javascript
// Get all books
app.get('/books', (req, res) => {
  res.json(books);
});

// Search for books by title or author
app.get('/books/search', (req, res) => {
  const { title, author } = req.query;
  let filteredBooks = books;

  if (title) {
    filteredBooks = filteredBooks.filter(book => book.title.toLowerCase().includes(title.toLowerCase()));
  }

  if (author) {
    filteredBooks = filteredBooks.filter(book => book.author.toLowerCase().includes(author.toLowerCase()));
  }

  res.json(filteredBooks);
});

// Get a single book by ID
app.get('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const bookId = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === bookId);

  if (!book) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Book not found' });
  }

  res.json(book);
});

// Create a new book
app.post('/books', (req, res) => {
  const { title, author } = req.body;

  if (!title || !author) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Title and author are required' });
  }

  const newBook = { id: nextId++, title, author };
  books.push(newBook);
  res.status(201).json(newBook);
});

// Update an existing book
app.put('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const bookId = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const index = books.findIndex(b => b.id === bookId);

  if (index === -1) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Book not found' });
  }

  const { title, author } = req.body;

  if (!title || !author) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Title and author are required' });
  }

  books[index] = { id: bookId, title, author };
  res.json(books[index]);
});

// Delete a book
app.delete('/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const bookId = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const index = books.findIndex(b => b.id === bookId);

  if (index === -1) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Book not found' });
  }

  books.splice(index, 1);
  res.status(204).end();
});
```

6. Test the API

You can now test your RESTful API using tools like [Postman](https://www.postman.com/) or [curl](https://curl.se/).

To start the server, run:

```
node app.js
```

Your API should now be running on `http://localhost:3000`. You can use the following endpoints to manage your collection of books:

- `GET /books`: Get all books
- `GET /books/search?title={title}&author={author}`: Search for books by title or author
- `GET /books/:id`: Get a single book by ID
- `POST /books`: Create a new book (send JSON with `title` and `author`)
- `PUT /books/:id`: Update an existing book (send JSON with `title` and `author`)
- `DELETE /books/:id`: Delete a book

Here is a simple Java program that simulates a vending machine:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class VendingMachine {
    private static final double[] PRICES = {1.00, 2.50, 0.75, 3.00, 1.25};
    private static final String[] PRODUCTS = {"Coke", "Chips", "Water", "Snickers", "Gum"};

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Welcome to the Vending Machine!");
        while (true) {
            for (int i = 0; i < PRODUCTS.length; i++) {
                System.out.printf("%d. %s ($%.2f)\n", i + 1, PRODUCTS[i], PRICES[i]);
            }
            System.out.print("Please select a product or press 0 to exit: ");
            int choice = scanner.nextInt();
            if (choice == 0) {
                break;
            } else if (choice > 0 && choice <= PRODUCTS.length) {
                System.out.printf("You selected %s which costs $%.2f.\n", PRODUCTS[choice - 1], PRICES[choice - 1]);
                System.out.print("Please insert your money: ");
                double payment = scanner.nextDouble();
                while (payment < PRICES[choice - 1]) {
                    System.out.printf("Insufficient funds. Please insert at least $%.2f more: ", PRICES[choice - 1] - payment);
                    payment += scanner.nextDouble();
                }
                double change = payment - PRICES[choice - 1];
                if (change > 0) {
                    System.out.printf("Thank you! Your change is $%.2f.\n\n", change);
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Thank you! You have no change.\n");
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("Invalid selection. Please try again.");
            }
        }
        System.out.println("Thank you for using our Vending Machine!");
        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

This program first displays all available products with their prices and asks the user to make a selection. If the user chooses an invalid option, they are asked to try again. If they choose a valid product, they are then prompted to insert money. If the inserted amount is less than the price of the product, they are asked to insert more until the total is sufficient. If the total inserted amount is greater than the price, the remaining change is calculated and returned to the user. The process repeats until the user decides to exit by pressing 0.

// Function to swap case of each letter in a string
function swapCase(str) {
    // Initialize an empty string for the result
    var result = "";

    // Loop through each character in the string
    for (var i = 0; i < str.length; i++) {
        // If the current character is uppercase, convert it to lowercase and add it to the result
        if (str[i] === str[i].toUpperCase()) {
            result += str[i].toLowerCase();
        }
        // If the current character is lowercase, convert it to uppercase and add it to the result
        else {
            result += str[i].toUpperCase();
        }
    }

    // Return the resulting string
    return result;
}

