Here is a simple JavaScript function that uses a regular expression to validate email addresses:

```javascript
function validateEmail(email) {
    var re = /^(([^<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))@((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))$/;
    return re.test(String(email).toLowerCase());
}
```

This function checks if the provided string matches the pattern defined by the regular expression. The regular expression covers most common forms of valid email addresses, but it's worth noting that the full specification for what constitutes a valid email address is quite complex and this regex does not cover every possible case.

You can use this function like so:

```javascript
console.log(validateEmail("name@example.com")); // Outputs: true
console.log(validateEmail("not an email")); // Outputs: false
```

